05399nam a22009855i 9780520956681DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20132013cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2020757097  a97805209566817 a10.1525/97805209566812doi  a(DE-B1597)519261  a(OCoLC)852656157  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aJK468.I6 4aE741 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a973.922231 aFriedman, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCovert Capital :bLandscapes of Denial and the Making of U.S. Empire in the Suburbs of Northern Virginia /cAndrew Friedman. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (428 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Crossroads ;v3700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Covert Intimacies of Langley and Dulles -- t2. At Home with the CIA -- t3. Saigon Road: The Co-Constituted Landscape of Northern Virginia and South Vietnam -- t4. The Fall of South Vietnam and the Transnational Intimacies of Falls Church, Arlington, and McLean -- t5. Iran-Contra as Built Space: U.S. Imperial Tehran in Exile and Edge City’s Central American Presence -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe capital of the U.S. Empire after World War II was not a city. It was an American suburb. In this innovative and timely history, Andrew Friedman chronicles how the CIA and other national security institutions created a U.S. imperial home front in the suburbs of Northern Virginia. In this covert capital, the suburban landscape provided a cover for the workings of U.S. imperial power, which shaped domestic suburban life. The Pentagon and the CIA built two of the largest office buildings in the country there during and after the war that anchored a new imperial culture and social world. As the U.S. expanded its power abroad by developing roads, embassies, and villages, its subjects also arrived in the covert capital as real estate agents, homeowners, builders, and landscapers who constructed spaces and living monuments that both nurtured and critiqued postwar U.S. foreign policy. Tracing the relationships among American agents and the migrants from Vietnam, El Salvador, Iran, and elsewhere who settled in the southwestern suburbs of D.C., Friedman tells the story of a place that recasts ideas about U.S. immigration, citizenship, nationalism, global interconnection, and ethical responsibility from the post-WW2 period to the present. Opening a new window onto the intertwined history of the American suburbs and U.S. foreign policy, Covert Capital will also give readers a broad interdisciplinary and often surprising understanding of how U.S. domestic and global histories intersect in many contexts and at many scales.American Crossroads, 37  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFederal areas within stateszVirginia. 0aIntelligence servicezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSuburbszVirginia, Northern. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  aamerican history.  aamerican suburbs.  acapitalism.  acentral intelligence agency.  acia.  acitizenship.  aclose knit communities.  acold war.  ademocracy.  adiplomacy.  aengaging.  aforeign policy.  aglobal interconnection.  ahistory.  aimperial power.  ainternational relations.  anationalism.  aneighbors.  anorthern virginia.  apage turner.  apolitical geography.  apolitics.  apostwar america.  arelationships.  aretrospective.  asuburban landscape.  athe pentagon.  aunited states history.  aus foreign policy.  aus immigration.  avirginia.  awashington dc.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyter